    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>Robert E. Schwartz (Bob) was born on October 17, 1928 in Midland, Michigan, to Vera and Russell Schwartz. He graduated from Midland High School in 1946 and from the College of Architecture and Design at the University of Michigan in 1954. A Midlan resident his entire life, he had an active architecture practice there until the time of his death. The Schwartz House, which he designed and in which he and his wife, Barbara, lived, is eligible for the National Register of Historic Places for its association with the modern architecture movement in Michigan.</p>
      <p>Mr. Schwartz belonged to the University of Michigan President's Club, the Midland City Planning Commission, the Riverfront Beautification Committee and the Midland City Building Board of Appeals, among many others.</p>
      <p>He passed away on October 10, 2010.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The Robert E. Schwartz architectural drawings reflect the mid-century modern architectural design movement of the mid-20th century in the United States, especially that part of the movement that was employed in residential structures, although the collection contains drawings of his commercial structures as well. His residential structures exhibit fundamental characteristics of the Modern Movement including their simple geometric forms, lack of applied ornamentation, use of large expanses of glass to bring nature and sunlight into the structure, and their open, free-flowing floor plans. The collection has been maintained in the order received and is divided into two series: Architectural Drawings and Newspaper Clippings.</p>
    </scopecontent>
